text: Sure. So we're having a hard fork, we're calling it Constantinople, and it's coming up hopefully in October, right before Devcon. And part of that hard fork includes a number of eips, most of them uncontroversial, and just decided in core dev calls. But there were a few eips that were being debated by the community and by the core devs that involved an issuance reduction for block rewards. Whenever a miner mines a block in Ethereum, they get a reward of three ether. That reward used to be five ether, but last year we cut that reward down. And so this year, due to the fact that some people think we're paying too much for miners securing the network, we wanted to cut down the reward even more from three ether to something lower, like two ether or one ether. At least that's what the community maybe wanted. We couldn't get a clear signal on that. Last year we didn't include miners enough in that conversation. So this year I tried to communicate with as many miners as I could find and say, hey, this is being discussed, we're going to maybe cut the reward down again. What do you think about that? You're not going to make as much money, but we're technically overpaying for it. Some people think so. What are your opinions? And obviously they were against it. They thought it would lessen the security of the network. And there were people from the community who said it won't lessen security. We just need to be careful about it and we're overpaying for it. So because there was all this disagreement with how much to reduce it, if we were going to reduce it at all, we decided to get miners and people from the community on the core dev call, which is a very rare occurrence to get non core developers on a core dev call. So we had representation from at least three or four miners and then three or four community members, plus a lot of core developers and other people. And so they all got on the call and I moderated a 30 person call where they went back and forth on their pros and cons for each of their arguments. And at the end of the call, we didn't come to a decision. We spent a lot of the time hearing the arguments. And so someone suggested that we wait a week, have the community continue to duke it out online on Reddit and Twitter, et cetera, and then come back in a week and the core developers just decide what they think the community wants and implement that in code. Not even the arguments of the debate necessarily, but the arguments about how to tell from the community what they wanted, what signals, because there was like a coin vote that went on, and there were Twitter polls and there were Reddit threads and all kinds of stuff that could indicate one way or another, but those can get a lot of people from either the mining community or from the investor community that might go in and try to sabotage it or make fake accounts. So after all of this, we came to the conclusion that miners would be able to stay on the network if we did a reduction to two ether and as sort of a compromise, we were going to look into something called programmatic proof of work, which is an alternative to et hash, which is the current proof of work algorithm.
